==Religions==
===Bahá'í Faith=== The [[Bahá'í Faith]] has nearly one thousand members and nine centres in Catalonia as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fe Bahá'í — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Bahai.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927205136/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Bahai.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The first Bahá'í group in Catalonia was established in [[Barcelona]] in 1949, while the first formal centre was inaugurated in [[Terrassa]], in the [[Vallès Occidental]], in 1962. The Vallès Occidental is still the region where most of the Catalan Bahá'ís reside, and where six out of the nine Bahá'í centres are situated.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=122}} Most Bahá'ís are ethnic Catalan converts, while a small minority are immigrants of [[Iran]]ian or other origins.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=123}}
===Buddhism=== 1.3% of the Catalans identify as Buddhists as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> Buddhism has 68 temples in Catalonia as of the same year, holding their services in [[Catalan language|Catalan]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]] language, reflecting the ethnic origins of the Buddhist community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Budisme — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Budisme.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927130541/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Budisme.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The majority of Buddhists, though, are ethnic Catalan converts.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=76}} These practise a variety of traditions of Buddhism, collectively represented since 2007 by the Catalan Coordinator of Buddhist Entities (''Coordinadora Catalana d’Entitats Budistes'', CCEB).{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|pp=71–73}} Buddhist temples in Catalonia are mostly of the [[Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan]] (54%) and [[Zen]] (32%) traditions as of 2014, with the rest representing other traditions such as [[Pure Land Buddhism]] and [[Soka Gakkai]]'s [[Nichiren Buddhism]].{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=74}}
===Christianity=== 61.9% of the population of Catalonia identify as Christians as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" />
====Catholicism==== 58.0% of the Catalans identify as Catholics as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> There are 6,701 Catholic churches as of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Llocs de culte per confessió i comarca — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Info_Mapa_religios.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927212434/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Info_Mapa_religios.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>
====Orthodox Christianity and Eastern Catholicism==== 0.9% of the Catalans identify as Orthodox Christians as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> As of the same year, there are 55 Orthodox Christian and [[Eastern Catholic Churches|Eastern Catholic]] churches (most of them being Orthodox Christian) in the country, mostly for [[Romanian language|Romanian]] and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]-speaking communities (the few Eastern Catholic churches being of the [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church|Ukrainian Greek Catholic tradition]]), with a small proportion of [[Arabic]] and [[Greek language|Greek]]-speaking churches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Esglésias orientals — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_orientals.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927171352/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_orientals.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>
====Protestantism==== [[File:051 Església evangèlica.jpg|thumb|[[Rubí, Barcelona|Rubí]] Evangelical Church, is a historical Protestant church in the city.]] 3.0% of the Catalans identify as Protestants or Evangelicals as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> As of 2014 there are 725 Protestant and Evangelical churches in Catalonia, which conduct their services mostly in Spanish, Catalan, [[English language|English]], Romanian, and a minority in [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Brazilian Portuguese]] and African languages. Many followers are immigrants from [[South America]], Africa and [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Esglésies evangèliques — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Evageliques.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927144012/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Evageliques.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> Most churches are Evangelical, 469 of them belonging to [[Pentecostalism]], while historical Protestantism ([[Anglicanism]], [[Lutheranism]], [[Methodism]], [[Presbyterianism]]) is represented by less than 20% of the churches.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|pp=33–34}}
====Restorationism====
=====Adventism===== The [[Seventh-day Adventist Church]] has about 1,500 members in Catalonia, belonging to 24 churches. Most of these churches hold their services in Spanish and Catalan, with a minority using Romanian, and an even smaller minority using languages of [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Església Adventista del Setè Dia — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Adventista.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927202346/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Adventista.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>
=====Jehovah's Witnesses===== [[File:Sala del Regne dels Testimonis Cristians de Jehovà - C. Doctor Aiguader.jpg|thumb|Kingdom hall in Barcelona.]] 0.6% of the Catalans identify as Jehovah's Witnesses as of 2014.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> As of the same year, there are 118 Jehovah's [[kingdom hall]]s in the country, found in all [[comarca|co-marches]] of Catalonia but with a high concentration in the [[province of Barcelona]]. Most Jehovah's Witnesses are ethnic Catalans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testimonis Cristians de Jehovà — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Testimonis.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927200020/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Testimonis.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>
=====Mormonism===== The [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], the major body of [[Mormonism]], has more than 6,000 members and 15 places of worship as of 2014, most of them using Spanish as their liturgical language.<ref>{{cite web|title=Església de Jesucrist dels Sants dels Darrers Dies — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Sants_Darrers_Dies.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927203850/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Sants_Darrers_Dies.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> Many Mormons in Catalonia are South American immigrants, and this is the reason why Spanish is the primary language of the Mormon communities in the country.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=109}}
===Germanic Heathenry=== [[Germanic Heathenry]] is represented in Catalonia by "Gotland Forn Sed" ([[North Germanic languages|Scandinavian Germanic]] for "Gothland Old Belief"). Catalonia in the early [[Middle Ages]] was known as the [[March of Gothia]] within the [[Carolingian Empire]]. It was an area of settlement of [[Visigoths]] and the same name "Catalonia" (''Catalunya'') is traditionally explained as being an alteration of "Gothland", through the [[Latin]]isation ''Gothalandia'', and then the early alteration ''Cathalaunia''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ulick Ralph Burke|title=A History of Spain from the Earliest Times to the Death of Ferdinand the Catholic|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tz3g_YzTQaUC&pg=PA154|year=1900|publisher=Longmans, Green, and co.|page=154}}</ref>
===Hinduism=== [[Hinduism]] has 27 temples in Catalonia as of 2014, 14 of which are situated in the province of Barcelona. The religion is mostly represented by [[India]]n immigrants, though there is also a significant number of Catalan converts. Indeed, the vast majority of Hindu temples hold their services in Catalan or Spanish language.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hinduisme — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_hinduisme.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927135544/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_hinduisme.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|pp=98–100}} Hindus in Catalonia follow a variety of traditions of worship and thought.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=97}}
===Islam=== 4.8% of the population of Catalonia identify as Muslims as of 2016.<ref name="Barometer2016" /> There are 256 [[mosque]]s in Catalonia as of the same year, most of them holding their services in [[Arabic]], with a smaller proportion of mosques serving in [[Urdu]] and an even smaller one in some [[Africa]]n languages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Islam — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Islam.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927133522/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_Islam.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> Nearly all mosques are of the [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] tradition, with only one mosque representing [[Shia Islam]]. There are also six [[Sufism|Sufi]] centres.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=48}} As of 2014 there are five organisations of Muslims in Catalonia: the Catalan Islamic Federation (''Federació Islàmica Catalana''), the Islamic Federative Council of Catalonia (''Federació Consell Islàmic de Catalunya''), the Union of Islamic Communities of Catalonia (''Unió de Comunitats Islàmiques de Catalunya''), the Union of Islamic Cultural Centres of Catalonia (''Unió de Centres Culturals Islàmics de Catalunya'') and an umbrella organisation, the Islamic Junta (''Junta Islàmica'').{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=49}}
===Judaism=== [[File:555 Casa de Sant Jordi, o Sinagoga, c. Major de Remolins 44 - cantonada tv. Mur (Tortosa).JPG|thumb|Ancient synagogue in [[Tortosa]].]] [[Jews]] in Catalonia are about 15,000 as of 2014, and there are four [[synagogue]]s in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judaisme — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_judaisme.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928101520/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_judaisme.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=28 September 2017}}</ref> Not all Jews are followers of the [[Judaism|Jewish religion]]. Indeed, 80% of Jews in Catalonia are non-religious or secular, while only 20% are observant. The Israelitic Community of Barcelona (''Comunitat Israelita de Barcelona'', CIB), is the oldest Jewish religious community in Catalonia, founded in 1918, and follows [[Orthodox Judaism]]. In 1992 the Jewish Community Atid of Catalonia (''Comunitat Jueva Atid de Catalunya'') was established as a splinter of the CIB, adopting [[Reform Judaism]]. In the early 2000s a [[Chabad|Chabad-Lubavitch]], [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]], outreach centre was founded in Catalonia. In 2006 another Reform group, the Progressive Jewish Community Bet Shalom, was founded as a splinter of Atid.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=131}}
Ethnically, Jews who belong to the CIB are predominantly [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]], although there is a small minority of [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi]] as well. Members of Atid are, instead, mostly of South American origin, specifically [[Argentina|Argentines]]. Endly, Bet Shalom predominantly hosts ethnic Catalan converts, and other minorities of converts without ethnic Jewish origin.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=134}}
===Sikhism=== [[Sikhism]] in Catalonia has ten temples ([[gurdwara]]s) as of 2014 and some thousands of believers. Virtually all Sikhs are [[Punjabis]] who immigrated from the [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] region of India, Sikhism being strongly linked to the Punjabi ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sikhisme — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_sikhisme.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927194342/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_sikhisme.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref>
===Taoism=== [[Taoism]] has six registered temples in Catalonia as of 2014, most of them holding their services in Catalan or Spanish language.<ref>{{cite web|title=Taoisme — Mapa Religiós de Catalunya|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_taoisme.pdf|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance and Institutional Relations, General Direction of Religious Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927141258/http://governacio.gencat.cat/web/.content/afers_religiosos/documents/Mapa_2014/2014_Fitxa_taoisme.pdf|date=2014|archive-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> Of these temples, five are situated in the province of Barcelona, where most [[Chinese people|Chinese]] immigrants, who the temples serve, are gathered. There are also many ethnic Catalan converts.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=128}} Catalan Taoists have established the Taoist Association of Catalonia (''Associació Taoista de Catalunya''), led by the Chinese [[Taoist priest]] Tian Chengyang, while at the same time there are many Chinese Taoist centres which do not use Catalan language and do not integrate in the broader society.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=129}}
The first Taoist group in Catalonia was established in 1979 by a Catholic priest of Chinese origin, Peter Yang, who proposed a synthesis of Taoism and Christianity. All the other centres have been established from 2000 onwards.{{sfn|ISOR researchers|2014|p=128}} Another [[:ca:Temple Taoista de Barcelona|Taoist temple]] was opened in 2014 by the Chinese of Barcelona, led by master Liu Zemin, a 21st-generation descendant of poet, soldier and prophet [[Liu Bowen]] (1311-1375). The temple, located in the district of [[Sant Martí (district)|Sant Martí]] and inaugurated in the presence of the People's Republic of China consul Qu Chengwu, enshrines 28 [[Chinese gods and immortals|deities]] of the province of China where most of the Chinese in Barcelona come from.<ref>{{cite web|title=S'ha inaugurat un temple taoista a Barcelona|url=http://governacio.gencat.cat/ca/detalls/Noticia/013_taoista|publisher=Government of Catalonia, Department of Governance, Public Administration and Housing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928093534/http://governacio.gencat.cat/ca/detalls/Noticia/013_taoista|date=2014|archive-date=28 September 2017}}</ref>
==Irreligion, atheism and agnosticism== 27.9% of the Catalans identify as irreligious as of 2016. Of them, 16.0% are atheists and 11.9% are agnostics.<ref name=Barometer2016/>
